> There is something so comforting about this recipe. Sometimes the most simple ingredients come together to create something absolutely wonderful, which is what happened here when chef Rachel decided to make this dish. She hit the comfort food nail on the head with this light, vibrant broth and a nice helping of smooth warming mash. We hope you enjoy it as much as all of us!

Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Peel the @Maris Piper Potatoes{2} and chop into (roughly) 2cm cubes. Cook the potatoes over medium heat for ~{15-20%minutes} until you can easily slip a knife through them, then drain.

Peel and chop the @onion{3}(peeled and finely chopped) in half through the root, then very thinly slice into half moon shapes. Peel and finely chop the @garlic{2%cloves}(finely chopped). Wash the @leek{3} and finely chop into 1cm discs. Peel and chop the @carrot{2} into less than ½cm cubes. Finely chop the @tarragon{2}(finely chopped, stalks discarded).

Heat @oil{2%tbsp} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Mix the @flour{2%tbsp} with @salt{1/2%tsp} and @pepper{}, dip the @British Chicken Thighs{8} in and pat off any excess flour. Add to the pan and allow to colour for ~{3-4%minutes} on one side, turn over and cook for ~{1%minute} and then remove.

> The flour will help to tenderise the chicken and thicken the sauce later.

In the same pan, turn the heat down to medium and add the onion, garlic, leek and carrot, allow to soften for ~{4%minutes}.

> If the pan goes too dry add a drop of water.

Return the chicken along with half the @chicken stock pot{1} and @water{400%ml}. Cover with a #lid{} and cook for ~{10%minutes}, remove the lid and allow the sauce to reduce by half. Now add the @cider vinegar{2 tbsp}.

Mash the potatoes once they are cooked and drained with a #potato masher{}. Add @salt{1/4%tsp}, @pepper{}, @milk{5%tbsp} and @?butter{2%tbsp}.

When the chicken is cooked and the sauce has reduced by half, taste for seasoning and add more salt or pepper to your liking. Finally add the tarragon.

Serve the chicken stew on top of your creamy mash.